The problem isn’t you loving cheese-it’s the  lack of discipline. I’m not saying you have to give up cheese forever. But let’s say you go all in for 2 months. Cutting back on cheese, wine, the “need” for sweets every single evening. 

And you start to feel better, scale goes down, confidence starts to go up, clothes fit better, it becomes easier- you get addicted to how you look and feel-and realize it was never about cheese! It’s just an excuse you kept using to stay the same. 

You have to stop finding reasons to take care of yourself. Or you’re going to spend the rest of your days wishing and dreaming about it, instead of working towards it. 

That’s. Not. Living. 
That’s prison. 

Biggest lesson I ever learned is your new life is going to cost you your own old. And maybe not everything, but habits that are holding you back will have to go. 

Nothing changes if nothing changes

I’m going to tell you this. Faster way isn’t the only way-it’s not going to give you overnight success-so if that’s the only thing you’re looking for-
do. Not. Sign. Up. 

It’s going to give you the FOUNDATION, the principles, the guidance, the accountability that will give you success if you work for it. 

The reason I still coach it is because it works. (And works so well) that I don’t want women to get scammed by another quick fix. I’m a damn good coach, but I’m not a magician -I can’t come cook for you or make you do the workouts 

The best program for you is the one you’ll commit to  NICKI50 for $50 off my Monday round

We are halfway thru the year 
and you’re still starting over. 
You’ve had 6 months to get serious 
and yet you are still doing the same habits, 
rewriting the same goals, 
replaying the same excuses. 

You’ve done more scrolling than working. 
More talking than tracking. 
You’ve romanticized the change 
but you haven’t earned it.

You don’t need more signs, another podcast 
episode or influencer telling you to start. You 
honestly don’t need supplements. 
You don’t need another cheat day that
 turns into 2 weeks of self sabotage 

This level isn’t going to reward you for “trying”. It’s gonna come after the reps, the effort
, the tracking, meal planning, 
after the consistency, the effort 

You say you’re overwhelmed- 
but you still have time to binge shows, 
overthink texts, and scroll
 past the life you say you want 

At some point it’s not burnout, it’s avoidance. 

It’s you standing in your own way. So if the first 6 months were chaos, fine. Let the last 6 months be discipline, effort and stop gas lighting yourself. 

No one is coming to force you to change. You have to choose that everyday. Quietly, relentlessly

It took me almost 18 months to get where I am now. What seems like “overnight” was actually years of trial and errors. 

For 3 years I gaslight myself-wondering why it wasn’t “sticking” when I knew I wasn’t actually doing the work 

I tracked macros like a psychopath this year, added a TON of cardio in prep for Hyrox, carb cycled (even added an extra low carb day cuz my body responds well to it), hormones tested, and rarely drink alcohol now. 

I’m not saying it was easy (or sustainable long term) but I’m also not going to let someone take my hard work away from me

I’ve been loose with tracking macros and more in maintenance since 
May and have gained 4 lbs! 
(Haven’t tracked much) 

From August-Dec 2024 I was in muscle building (higher cal, tons of protein) and then I was in a very strict deficit from Jan-May to shed the fat on top of the muscle gained to prep for our anniversary trip! Although it worked, It’s  unrealistic for me to stay there long term! 

Being here has allowed me to still enjoy summer without obsessing over every bite 

Everyone has different goals but this is my happy place

The tracking. The knowing what to eat. 
The substitutions. 
The planning. The questions become spaced out. 
The terror starts to diminish. You fluster less.

but staying the same is much harder. 

It won’t always be frustrating. You will learn and  it will settle into your beautiful brain, nice and cozy, and it won’t go anywhere for life. It will become a part of you, and it will become second nature.

That’s a promise I’m making you.

Creatine is an osmotically active substance, meaning it draws water into muscle cells for repair and recovery. 

This can lead to a increase in water weight, especially when starting but it’s TEMPORARY. 

It doesn’t make you gain fat so even if the scale is going up-it’s likely water weight. 

That’s why I hate traditional scales cuz it’s not showing the full picture. 

Just keep your cute butt off the scale for awhile and focus on how you feel, measurements and how your clothes fit

I cut back on booze at the beginning of the year because I was SO sick of how it made me feel-wasn’t even thinking for my fitness goals. 

Our kids get up by 6 am every day and it just wasn’t worth the insane anxiety, lack of patience with kids, mood swings, not wanting to workout, etc as I get older. 

I still enjoy a few drinks with my friends on the weekends but I don’t get too crazy and rarely drink during the week. 

Booze impacts fat loss-without question. It turns all its attention to metabolising the alcohol and stops burning fat every time you drink. 

I’ll never be the person who judges you for drinking-you have to decide what’s a lifestyle for you -but don’t expect a ton of results fast with drinking wine every night
